 OS-Level Network Configuration

---

 1️⃣ Ethernet Card (NIC)

 Every Linux machine has at least one network interface card (NIC).
 Examples: `eth0`, `eth1`, `eth2`
 Each NIC has a unique MAC address (Media Access Control) → like a hardware ID.

Special hardware:

 HBA (Host Bus Adapter) → for storage access, has WWN (World Wide Number)

---

 2️⃣ IP Address Basics

 IP = Internet Protocol address → like the house address of your machine.
 Example:

```
192.168.145.80 → unique address for one machine
```

 IPv4: 32 bits → 4 octets (e.g., 192.168.145.1)

 IPv6: 128 bits → larger address space (e.g., 11345ABC.2342DE3D.156ABE7E.88567EG7)

 Loopback IP: `127.0.0.1`

   Used internally within the machine for services like SSH, HTTP, NFS

---

 3️⃣ IP Classes

| Class | Purpose               | Range (Public) | Private Range           |
| ----- | --------------------- | -------------- | ----------------------- |
| A     | Large networks        | 1-126...    | 10...                |
| B     | Medium networks       | 128-191...  | 172.16.. – 172.31.. |
| C     | Small networks        | 192-223...  | 192.168..             |
| D     | Multicast             | 224-239...  | N/A                     |
| E     | Research/Experimental | 240-255...  | N/A                     |

Tip: If IP starts with `10`, it’s Class A private.

 Example:

```
10.1.1.2 → private
2.1.1.2  → public
172.1.1.4 → public
```

---

 4️⃣ Netmask

 Defines network vs host portion of IP
  | Network | Netmask |
  |---------|---------|
  | 10... | 255.0.0.0 |
  | 172.16.. | 255.255.0.0 |
  | 192.168.. | 255.255.255.0 |

 Remember: Netmask ≠ umask (umask → file permissions)

---

 5️⃣ Static vs Dynamic IP

 Static IP: fixed, recommended for servers
 Dynamic IP: assigned by DHCP server, may change over time

Set DHCP (dynamic) in Linux:

```bash
vi /etc/sysconfig/network-scripts/ifcfg-ens33
BOOTPROTO=dhcp
ONBOOT=yes
```

Set Static IP in Linux:

```bash
vi /etc/sysconfig/network-scripts/ifcfg-ens33
BOOTPROTO=static
ONBOOT=yes
IPADDR=192.168.145.100
NETMASK=255.255.255.0
GATEWAY=192.168.145.1
```

---

 6️⃣ Multiple IPs on a Single NIC

```bash
vi /etc/sysconfig/network-scripts/ifcfg-ens33
BOOTPROTO=static
ONBOOT=yes

IPADDR0=192.168.145.100
PREFIX0=24
GATEWAY0=192.168.145.1

IPADDR1=192.168.145.101
PREFIX1=24
GATEWAY1=192.168.145.1
```

---

 7️⃣ Gateway

 Acts as a single exit/entry point for all traffic from the network
 Simplifies monitoring → only one place to check traffic

-


                         WAN / Internet
                               |
                          +------------+
                          |  Firewall  |
                          +------------+
                               |
                          +------------+
                          |   Router   |
                          +------------+
                               |
                    ------------------------
                    |                      |
               LAN Switch 1             LAN Switch 2
            (Office / Building A)   (Office / Building B)
           /      |       \        /      |       \
       PC1      PC2      PC3    PC4      PC5      PC6
     eth0     eth0     eth0    eth0     eth0     eth0
   
   IP: static or dynamic
   Netmask / Gateway configured

PC (eth0/IP) → Switch → Router → Firewall → WAN / Internet
